Geology.
[underline]Lecture. 4[superscript]th[/superscript] 1805.[/underline]
- It has often happened during
the progress of Science that two
doctrines immediately opposite have
been supported with great powers of
reasoning & almost with equal plausibility.
Such a circumstance however
almost always marks with the infancy
of the study & the imperfection
of the methods of investigation.
It proves that speculation merely
has been employed or partial
facts only examined: And the
Philosophical enquirer in opposing
supposition to supposition & error
to error will instantly perceive

[page]4|MS-DAVY-00603-000-00004|dnpgs63_002pp|100776387[/page]
the insufficiency of either class of
opinions; & will thus preserve
the mind free from doubt, from
the prejudice of false systems,
& from mistake & confusion.
- This method may be [deletion]often[/deletion] [insertion]sometimes[/insertion]
applied with great success in
the examination of Geological
theories. - It [deletion]sometimes[/deletion] removes the
necessity of strict discussion &
it often devellopes absurdity without
the assistance of laborious logical
deductions.
[underline]Buffon[/underline] in his Theory of
the Globe, supposes that the
surface is constantly becoming
[underline]colder[/underline]. M. de Maillet on the

[page]5|MS-DAVY-00603-000-00005|dnpgs63_003pp|100776388[/page]
other hand conceives that it is daily growing
warmer. The first attempts to prove
that [deletion]the[/deletion] ice in the course of ages
will [underline]extend[/underline] even to the [deletion]line[/deletion] [insertion]countries under the tropics[/insertion] Whilst
the last conceives that in no
very [deletion]long[/deletion] distant period it will
[underline]disappear[/underline] even from the poles.
The one Author fears that [deletion]our[/deletion] unless
[insertion]the energies of Man are capable of opposing the laws of Nature[/insertion] our cultivated lands will become [deletion][unclear]converted[/unclear][/deletion]
[deletion]into[/deletion] snow clad plains; & the
other dreads [deletion][unclear]xx[/unclear][/deletion] their conversion
into burning desarts of sand, [deletion][unclear]xxx[/unclear][/deletion]
incapable of supporting vegetable
life. -
It is scarcely possible to imagine
two Hypotheses in [deletion][unclear]xxxxx[/unclear][/deletion] more
perfect opposition; both have [insertion]been[/insertion] defended
with ingenuity, both are founded
upon mistakes. The one may
be ballanced against the other

[page]6|MS-DAVY-00603-000-00006|dnpgs63_004pp|100776389[/page]
there will be scarcely a perceptible
difference in their weight &
importance; & they may safely
be given up together. -
